ame exact model, so a little bit of randomness and variety I think is a pre=
tty important thing to shoot for. Today, we just live in a world where we w=
ere talking about how it took two-and-a-half years for someone to make that=
 teleprompter thing. It's going to take, I don't know what, two to four yea=
rs for someone to make something like that.

*NF:* Yeah, I mean, one demo I saw last year that I thought was one of the =
coolest demos of the year, I think people remember Golden Gate Claude ( htt=
ps://www.anthropic.com/news/golden-gate-claude ) , where Anthropic used som=
e interpretability work to find the Golden Gate Bridge feature in the model=
 and then turn that up to 11. And after they did that, when you interacted =
with Golden Gate Claude, it kept bringing up the Golden Gate Bridge or thou=
ght it was the Golden Gate Bridge, and it was just like this funny, comedic=
 thing.

But there's been some independent efforts to do that kind of thing and trai=
n these, what are called sparse auto encoders to find the features inside t=
he models and then allow you to adjust them. Daniel and I invested a little=
 bit in a company called Goodfire ( https://www.goodfire.ai/ ) that built o=
ne of these, and it's really neat. You can take a Llama model and you can h=
ave some interaction with it, you prompt it, you ask it a question, it give=
s you an answer, and then it'll show you in a sidebar all the features that=
 were lit up during that answer, and so there might be a feature about help=
fulness or there might be a feature about some of the topics you were discu=
ssing. So you asked a question about Eastern Europe and so, I don't know, s=
ome Romanian feature got triggered and then you can adjust those with slide=
rs to turn them up or down, and you can search for features. So you can fin=
d the pirate feature and turn that up and then it starts talking like a pir=
ate while it answers you, or you can find the niceness feature or the direc=
tness feature.

So it's the closest I've seen to a personality designer that's not just str=
aight prompting where you ask it to behave in certain ways, and the nice th=
ing about it is that it seems to be more powerful. You're closer to the met=
al in terms of adjusting these features, whereas prompting it can be diffic=
ult to override the fine-tuning and the RLHF that's in there. So yeah, that=
's the only demo I've seen that started to come close to the Photoshop for =
personality, but I thought it was really neat.

*You mentioned Llama, I mean if these V3, these DeepSeek models, actually e=
nd up being much cheaper and continue to be open source, perhaps in pursuit=
 of dominating this commodity market, does this end up being the ultimate C=
hinese propaganda victory that the base model for all these things is Chine=
se?*

*DG:* I think there's that science called linguistic relativity ( https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linguistic_relativity ) , that culture is shaped by la=
nguage and in a sense, maybe this is the closest thing that's happened prev=
iously, is the invention of language. LLMs are a little bit like that, and =
the question is, if you believe in this theory, it's really important to yo=
u that Latin subsequently, maybe English is the language of the western wor=
ld, if you believe the theory and so in that sense, I think we're going thr=
ough that same fight of who wins, what kind of culture and language win the=
 proliferation war?

*Well, on that note, we should not wait so long, it was good to talk to bot=
h of you again and thanks for coming on.*

